   "source": [
    "# Distributional models"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import arviz as az\n",
    "import bambi as bmb\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "\n",
    "from matplotlib.lines import Line2D"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import warnings\n",
    "warnings.simplefilter(action='ignore', category=FutureWarning) # ArviZ\n",
    "\n",
    "az.style.use(\"arviz-doc\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "For most regression models, a function of the mean (aka the location parameter) of the response distribution is defined as a linear function of certain predictors, while the remaining parameters are considered auxiliary. For instance, if the response is a Gaussian, we model $\\mu$ as a combination of predictors and $\\sigma$ is estimated from the data, but assumed to be constant for all observations.\n",
    "\n",
    "Instead, with distributional models we can specify predictor terms for all parameters of the response distribution. This can be useful, for example, to model heteroskedasticity, i.e. unequal variance. In this notebook we are going to do exactly that. \n",
    "\n",
    "To better understand distributional models, let's begin fitting a non-distributional models. We are going to model the following syntetic dataset. And we are going to use a Gamma response with a `log` link function."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "rng = np.random.default_rng(121195)\n",
    "N = 200\n",
    "a, b = 0.5, 1.1\n",
    "x = rng.uniform(-1.5, 1.5, N)\n",
    "shape = np.exp(0.3 + x * 0.5 + rng.normal(scale=0.1, size=N))\n",
    "y = rng.gamma(shape, np.exp(a + b * x) / shape, N)\n",
    "data = pd.DataFrame({\"x\": x, \"y\": y})\n",
    "new_data = pd.DataFrame({\"x\": np.linspace(-1.5, 1.5, num=50)})"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Constant alpha"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "       Formula: y ~ x\n",
       "        Family: gamma\n",
       "          Link: mu = log\n",
       "  Observations: 200\n",
       "        Priors: \n",
       "    target = mu\n",
       "        Common-level effects\n",
       "            Intercept ~ Normal(mu: 0.0, sigma: 2.5037)\n",
       "            x ~ Normal(mu: 0.0, sigma: 2.8025)\n",
       "        \n",
       "        Auxiliary parameters\n",
       "            alpha ~ HalfCauchy(beta: 1.0)"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 4,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "formula = bmb.Formula(\"y ~ x\")\n",
    "model_constant = bmb.Model(formula, data, family=\"gamma\", link=\"log\")\n",
    "model_constant"
   ]
  },

    "Once the model is fitted let's visually inspect the result in terms of the mean (the line in the following figure) and the individual predictions (the band)."
   ]

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "model_constant.predict(idata_constant, kind=\"mean\", data=new_data)\n",
    "model_constant.predict(idata_constant, kind=\"pps\", data=new_data)\n",
    "\n",
    "qts_constant = (\n",
    "    az.extract(idata_constant.posterior_predictive, var_names=\"y\")\n",
    "    .quantile([0.025, 0.975], \"sample\")\n",
    "    .to_numpy()\n",
    ")\n",
    "mean_constant = (\n",
    "    az.extract(idata_constant.posterior_predictive, var_names=\"y\")\n",
    "    .mean(\"sample\")\n",
    "    .to_numpy()\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },

    "\n",
    "az.plot_hdi(new_data[\"x\"], qts_constant, ax=ax, fill_kwargs={\"alpha\": 0.4})\n",
    "ax.plot(new_data[\"x\"], mean_constant, color=\"C0\", lw=2)\n",
    "ax.scatter(data[\"x\"], data[\"y\"], color=\"k\", alpha=0.2)\n",
    "ax.set(xlabel=\"Predictor\", ylabel=\"Outcome\");"

   "source": [
    "The model correctly model that the outcome increases with the values of the predictor. So far so good, let's dive into the heart of the matter."
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Varying alpha\n",
    "\n",
    "Now we are going to build the same model as before with the only, but crucial difference, that we are also going to make alpha depend on the predictor. The syntax is very simple besides the usual \"y ~ x\", we now add \"alpha ~ x\". Neat! "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "       Formula: y ~ x\n",
       "                alpha ~ x\n",
       "        Family: gamma\n",
       "          Link: mu = log\n",
       "                alpha = log\n",
       "  Observations: 200\n",
       "        Priors: \n",
       "    target = mu\n",
       "        Common-level effects\n",
       "            Intercept ~ Normal(mu: 0.0, sigma: 2.5037)\n",
       "            x ~ Normal(mu: 0.0, sigma: 2.8025)\n",
       "    target = alpha\n",
       "        Common-level effects\n",
       "            alpha_Intercept ~ Normal(mu: 0.0, sigma: 1.0)\n",
       "            alpha_x ~ Normal(mu: 0.0, sigma: 1.0)"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 9,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "formula_varying = bmb.Formula(\"y ~ x\", \"alpha ~ x\")\n",
    "model_varying = bmb.Model(formula_varying, data, family=\"gamma\", link={\"mu\": \"log\", \"alpha\": \"log\"})\n",
    "model_varying"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,

    "Now, with both models being fitted, let's see how the alpha parameter differs between both models. In the next figure you can see a blueish KDE for the alpha parameter estimated with `model_constant` and 200 black KDEs for the alpha parameter estimated from the `model_varying`. You can count it if you want :-), but we know they should be 200 because we should have one for each one of the 200 observations."
   ]
  },

    "    values = idata_varying.posterior[\"alpha\"].sel(y_obs=idx).to_numpy().flatten()\n",
    "    grid, pdf = az.kde(values)\n",
    "    ax.plot(grid, pdf, lw=0.05, color=\"k\")\n",

  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This is nice statistical art and a good insight into what the model is actully doing. But at this point you may be wondering how results looks like and more important how different they are from `model_constant`. Let's plot the mean and predictions as we did before, but for both models."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "model_varying.predict(idata_varying, kind=\"mean\", data=new_data)\n",
    "model_varying.predict(idata_varying, kind=\"pps\", data=new_data)\n",
    "\n",
    "qts_varying = (\n",
    "    az.extract(idata_varying.posterior_predictive, var_names=\"y\")\n",
    "    .quantile([0.025, 0.975], \"sample\")\n",
    "    .to_numpy()\n",
    ")\n",
    "mean_varying = (\n",
    "    az.extract(idata_varying.posterior_predictive, var_names=\"y\")\n",
    "    .mean(\"sample\")\n",
    "    .to_numpy()\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

     "data": {

    "We can see that mean is virtually the same for both model but the predictions are not, in particular for larger values of the predictiors. \n",
    "\n",

  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Distributional models with splines\n",
    "\n",
    "Time to step up our game. In this example we are going to use the bikes [data set](https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/bike+sharing+dataset) from the University of California Irvine’s Machine Learning Repository, and we are going to estimate the number of rental bikes rented per hour over a 24 hour period. \n",
    "\n",
    "As the number of bikes is a count variable we are going to use a `negativebinomial` family, and we are going to use two splines: one for the mean, and one for alpha."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "data = bmb.load_data(\"bikes\")\n",
    "# Remove data, you may later try to refit the model to the whole data\n",
    "data = data[::50]\n",
    "data = data.reset_index(drop=True)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "       Formula: count ~ 0 + bs(hour, 8, intercept=True)\n",
       "                alpha ~ 0 + bs(hour, 8, intercept=True)\n",
       "        Family: negativebinomial\n",
       "          Link: mu = log\n",
       "                alpha = log\n",
       "  Observations: 348\n",
       "        Priors: \n",
       "    target = mu\n",
       "        Common-level effects\n",
       "            bs(hour, 8, intercept=True) ~ Normal(mu: [0. 0. 0. 0. 0. 0. 0. 0.], sigma: [11.3704 13.9185\n",
       "                11.9926 10.6887 10.6819 12.1271 13.623  11.366 ])\n",
       "\n",
       "    target = alpha\n",
       "        Common-level effects\n",
       "            alpha_bs(hour, 8, intercept=True) ~ Normal(mu: 0.0, sigma: 1.0)"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 17,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "formula = bmb.Formula(\n",
    "    \"count ~ 0 + bs(hour, 8, intercept=True)\",\n",
    "    \"alpha ~ 0 + bs(hour, 8, intercept=True)\"\n",
    ")\n",
    "model_bikes = bmb.Model(formula, data, family=\"negativebinomial\")\n",
    "model_bikes"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {
    "scrolled": false
   },
   "outputs": [

     ]
    },

    "hour = np.linspace(0, 23, num=200)\n",

    "model_bikes.predict(idata_bikes, data=new_data, kind=\"pps\")"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "metadata": {
    "scrolled": true
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [

      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"

   ],
   "source": [
    "q = [0.025, 0.975]\n",
    "dims = (\"chain\", \"draw\")\n",
    "\n",
    "mean = idata_bikes.posterior[\"count_mean\"].mean(dims).to_numpy()\n",
    "mean_interval = idata_bikes.posterior[\"count_mean\"].quantile(q, dims).to_numpy()\n",
    "y_interval = idata_bikes.posterior_predictive[\"count\"].quantile(q, dims).to_numpy()\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 4))\n",
    "ax.scatter(data[\"hour\"], data[\"count\"], alpha=0.3, color=\"k\")\n",
    "ax.plot(hour, mean, color=\"C3\")\n",
    "ax.fill_between(hour, mean_interval[0],mean_interval[1], alpha=0.5, color=\"C1\");\n",
    "az.plot_hdi(hour, y_interval, fill_kwargs={\"color\": \"C1\", \"alpha\": 0.3}, ax=ax);"
   ]
  },
